y moral challenges, The Ambiguity of Virtue tells the story of Van Tijn's work on behalf of her fellow Jews as the avenues that might save them were closed off. Between 1933 and 1940 Van Tijn helped organize Jewish emigration from Germany. After the Germans occupied Holland, she worked for the Nazi-appointed Jewish Council in Amsterdam and enabled many Jews to escape. Some later called her a heroine for the choices she made; others denounced her as a collaborator. Bernard Wasserstein's haunting narrative draws readers into the twilight world of wartime Europe, to expose the wrenching dilemmas that confronted Jews under Nazi occupation. Gertrude van Tijn's experience raises crucial questions about German policy toward the Jews, about the role of the Jewish Council, and about Dutch, American, and British responses to the persecution and mass murder of Jews on an unimaginable scale.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xNetherlands. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)zNetherlands. 0aJewish womenxBiographyxNetherlandsxAmsterdam. 0aJewish womenzNetherlandszAmsterdamvBiography. 0aJewsxPersecutionsxHistoryx20th centuryxNetherlands. 0aJewsxPersecutionszNetherlandsxHistoryy20th century. 0aJews, GermanxBiographyxNetherlandsxAmsterdam. 0aJews, GermanzNetherlandszAmsterdamvBiography. 0aWomen social workersxBiographyxNetherlandsxAmsterdamxAmsterdam (stad). 0aWomen social workerszNetherlandszAmsterdamvBiography. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJewsxNetherlandsxAmsterdam. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJewsxRescuexNetherlands. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJewsxRescuezNetherlands. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJewszNetherlandszAmsterdam. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Pa